record.title: Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts
record.detail: Founded in 1833 on the model of Scottish Mechanics' Institutes, the SMSA sought to provide further education for working men through lectures, classes and a library. Many of Sydney's foremost intellectuals, inventors and innovators were associated with it, and it influenced the development of both the University of Sydney and technical education in New South Wales. It still provides a library and lectures to Sydneysiders in 2009.

record.title: The School of Arts movement
record.detail: During the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, about 140 schools of arts or mechanics' institutes were established in Sydney by volunteers. They were independent community organisations, assisted by a small government subsidy, and they thrived as centres of local community life. Today, their legacy in Sydney is more than just the surviving buildings. Out of these humble voluntary operations developed the local public library, the modern community or neighbourhood centre, and formal systems of adult and technical education.

record.title: Finally
record.detail: British Mechanics' Institutes were educational establishments formed to provide adult education, particularly in technical subjects, to working men. Under Henry Carmichael's inspired leadership, the Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts was established in 1833 and ran Australia's first formal adult education program.

record.title: In
record.detail: The Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts was established in 1833 and in 1836 moved to its own purpose-built home at 275 Pitt Street.

record.title: As
record.detail: The Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts was the working man's university in the nineteenth century.

record.title: role
record.detail: Although the Reading Room is now the restaurant in the Arthouse Hotel on Pitt Street, there have been only minor alterations to the splendour of the interior design. The Mechanics' School's relocated library remains one of the largest fiction libraries in Australia.

record.title: The
record.detail: The Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts was one of several self-improvement societies and libraries in nineteenth-century Sydney but it differed from others in that it was set up to benefit the colony's working people. In this illustration, men from a wide cross-section of Sydney society are using the reading room - women would have been in the Ladies' Reading Room.

record.title: Some
record.detail: The Working Men's College established by the Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts in 1878 led to the formation of the Sydney Technical College and the Board of Technical Education.

The working-men's college is, perhaps, the most interesting apartment, it being a large hall with boarded ceiling and open timber principals, handsomely designed, as will be seen in our sketch (page 4). It is lighted from the ceiling by a lantern-light, of which all the sashes on either side open simultaneously by pulling a cord, thereby ensuring efficient ventilation. The room is fitted up with all manner of scien- tific apparatus and specimens of nature, among which we noticed the double head of a calf which had four eyes, three ears, and two noses, all tolerably perfect. School of Arts, Sydney. (1879, June 14). Illustrated Sydney News, p. 4. http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article63335539

record.title: In
record.detail: The Workingman's College formed by the Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts in 1878 became the basis of the Sydney Technical College and then the University of Technology, Sydney in 1988.
